title: For Sale/Trade:  Leupold Mk 4 4.5-14X50
postcontent:
Ok, the scope is not for sale. This is warning that someone is selling Leupold scopes that are counterfeit! I bought a gun and scope of a man and it had the Leupold MK 4 on it. I decided to sell the gun and scope separate and someone informed me that the scope was counterfeit. 
  I called Leupold and spoke with a tech. He said it is sadly true. Here are the keys to look for, the most used serial number on fakes is 8888SC, also on the turret cover it will have the Leupold "L" is printed on it. On real Leupolds there is a 6 digit serial number with a single letter, and it will have a small brass Leupold medallion set in the turret cover. 
   He aslo stated that most of these are coming from pawn shops and eBay. 
Please pass this info along to anyone you know. Personally Im going to take mine to gun shows and put it on the table to show people the difference, and what a $1000 mistake looks like. 

 John

Hi-Point model 995 carbine is produced in USA. Reliable for purposes of training, plinking and self-defense, and can be fired with reasonable accuracy out to 100-150 meters, especially if optical or red-dot sight is used. Its appearance is in the standard configuration, but it can be upgraded with after-market polymer stocks manufactured by ATI in USA. 

Hi-Point model 995 carbine is blow back-operated weapon which fires from closed bolt. Receiver is made from aluminum alloy, with stock (pistol grip, butt and forearm) being made from polymer. Bolt is of wrap-around type, with most of its weight being placed around the breech of the barrel. Cocking handle is located on the left side of the gun, ejection is to the right side only. There is no bolt hold-open device, but bolt can be manually locked back by pushing the cocking handle inwards once it is pulled all the way to the rear. Manual safety is located on the left side of the gun, above the grip. Magazines are inserted into pistol grip; (compatible with Hi-Point in respective calibers) can be used. Magazine release button is located at the base of the trigger guard. Standard sights are of open type, adjustable for range and windage. Optional Picatinny rail can be installed instead of the rear sight base; this will accept any compatible sighting device (a red-dot sight is a preferred type for pistol-caliber carbines). No rear sights are mounted on this Rifle.

title: For Sale:  Browning | FN Belgium Made Sweet 16 - 1947 16ga.
postcontent:
Serial X115** Browning sweet sixteen shotgun in good condition. Looking to sell and not interested in trades. Shotgun was inherited from my grandfather and have no real use/need for it.

Gun was manufactured in 1947 and according to my research and the Shirley/Vanderlinden book on Browing firearms:

1947 Post war Belgium made “X Prefix Series.” No serial number distinction between the Sweet 16 and the Standard 16 gauge A5. This is the “unmarked” Browning, era of the Sweet Sixteen.

These are among the rarest of the A5 Sweet Sixteen but are priced as standard 16 gauge A5s in value guides. This is the first year of standard production of the 2 ¾ inch chambered 16 gauge. It is also the last year of the non-engraved sweet sixteen. The popularity and success of the Sweet Sixteen from 1937 through 1947 earned it a permanent place in Browning marketing as the 1948 engraved “Sweet Sixteen.” 1947 is also the only year the 3 shot 2 ¾ 16ga was marketed in the USA. Getting one of these extremely rare original factory issued guns at a standard gun price is a trophy in itself.
